Philippines (Cordillera Administrative Region): Dengue Alert Declared
--------------------------------------------------------
Regional health officials raised a dengue alert region-wide following
over 360 admissions with one death reported since January [2003]. This
developed even as Department of Health of the Cordillera
Administrative Region (DOH-CAR) Information Officer Bonifacio
Bengwayan reported that all provincial, municipal, and barangay health
offices in the region have already instituted measures to control the
increasing number of dengue admissions.
In Baguio, Dr. Florence Reyes, chief of the Baguio Health Department
reported that the dengue alert was also raised in 48 of the city's 128
barangays. She said that dengue admissions in various hospitals reached
105 as of July 2003. Most of the suspected dengue patients are residents of
Barangays Kias, Irisan, and Camp 7.
Bonifacio, meanwhile, reported that Ifugao province has the highest
number of dengue admissions with 132, followed by Benguet with 68
cases, 42 in Mt. Provinces and an aggregate of 20 cases from the
remaining provinces of Kalinga, Apayao and Abra. Most of the patients,
according to health officials, were admitted at the start of the rainy season.
To control the increasing trend of dengue admissions, health officials
recommended that all sanitary inspectors should be mobilized to
actively inspect the surroundings of dengue-affected barangays. There
should also be a regular monitoring of water sources in the city and that all
food handlers should secure updated health certificates. [Dengue is not
transmitted through food. - Mod.JW].
In June 2003, a dengue outbreak was declared in Paracelis town in Mt.
Province.
[Byline: Harley F. Palangchao]
