Philippines (Mindanao): 2-fold Increase in Davao City
-------------------------------------------------------
City Health Medical Officer, Dr. Edilberto Estampa yesterday said the
dengue cases in the city has increased by 300 percent from the same
period of 2002. From 283 cases documented in 2002, it soared to 951
cases from January to June 2003. "The trend of
dengue in Davao City (is) supposedly [cyclical?] every 3 years, but lately it
does not follow that pattern any more because the rainfall is almost
[continuous] throughout the year," Estampa said. In 2002, the
months of October, August, & July had the most number of Dengue
cases, but this year CHO statistics showed that the number of cases
every month has been 2-fold greater.
Topping the list of places where dengue is prevalent is Talomo South
with 168 cases, Talomo North with 147 cases, Agdao with 98 cases,
Buhangin with 97 cases and Sasa with 58 cases.
Estampa said the records they have were based on the consolidated reports
of the hospitals in the city. According to Estampa, although the increase is
quite alarming, the doctors' diagnoses were based only on symptoms and
signs as there's no "confirmatory test" in Davao City. He said that
confirmatory testing [is only carried out in] Manila. However, if doctors find
the symptoms in the patient, they'll usually diagnose it as dengue.
Dengue fever is 2nd in the list of 10 leading causes of illness in the
city. Topping the list is acute upper respiratory infection, 3rd is
pneumonia followed by diarrhea and gastroenteritis, acute bronchitis,
essential hypertension, other disease of urinary system, respiratory
tuberculosis, influenza, and bronchitic emphysema.
