Philippines (Northern Luzon): Widespread Outbreak
-------------------------------------------------
Like the other regions and provinces in Northern Luzon, the rainy
season disease dengue hemorrhagic fever has already made its dreaded
presence felt in Ilocos Sur. From January to July 2003, dengue afflicted a
total of 97 residents, mostly schoolchildren and
preschoolers, with 2 deaths, according to data provided by the
Provincial Health Team Office (PHTO).
As of 11 Aug 2003, half of the 32 towns and 2 cities in the province
have been afflicted by the disease since February this year. Hardest
hit were Candon City and the towns of San Ildefonso and Salcedo with 17,
16, and 12 victims, respectively. Other towns have the following number of
cases: San Juan, 8; San Vicente, 7; Sinait, Sto. Domingo & Vigan City, 6
each; Magsingal, 4; Bantay & Tagudin, 3 each; Caoayan & Lidlidda, 2 each;
Cabugao, Santa, Burgos & Del Pilar, 1 each.
The 2 patients who died of dengue were from the towns of Tagudin and
Vigan City.
The PHTO said the highest incidence was in July [2003] with 51 victims. This
number is more than twice the incidence in June, when 23 victims were
afflicted with the disease. The town of San Ildefonso had the highest number
of victims, 11 in July, followed by Candon City with 8. There have been only
12 victims yet this month as of 11 Aug 2003. The dengue incidence was low
in February with 3 victims, March with 1, April with 2 and May with 5. The 3
victims in February were from the towns of San Vicente, 2, & Caoayan 1.
The 3 victims in March (1) and April (2) were from Salcedo, and increased
to 4 in May [2003].
In Candon City, which is hardest hit by the disease thus far, dengue
incidence has been rising since May [2003], when there was only one
victim. The number rose to 5 in June & 8 in July. Thus far, however, only 3
have been afflicted with the disease in August.
A total of 11 of the 17 towns without dengue incidence are in the
interior areas of the province.
At the regional level, the Department of Health regional office in the
Cordillera also reported an alarming increase of dengue from 62 cases in
2002 to 353 this year with one death. Most of the patients were admitted to
hospitals at the start of the rainy season, health
officials said. Ifugao has the highest number of cases with 132,
followed by Baguio, 94; Benguet, 65; Mt. Province, 42; & Kalinga, 3,
according to officials.
