Source: Australian Broadcasting Corporation, Regional News Online, Wed
13 Aug 2003 [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/northqld/news/200308/s923005.htm>

Queensland; 3 Weeks Since Last Case Reported in Townsville
--------------------------------------------------------------
Townsville's Tropical Public Health Unit says the twin cities need
another 2 months free of any new dengue fever cases before it can
declare the recent outbreak is over. It is 3 weeks since the last case
was reported, but there are 20 confirmed cases in Townsville, and the unit
has been working with Townsville City Council for the past 4-5 months to
ensure its spread is minimised.
The director of environmental health, John Piispanen, says the weather is
playing into authorities' hands. "We're nearly at a month, so it's a bit early to
get too excited, but the signs are good," he said. "The cool weather means
the breeding cycle is a little bit longer, so it means less mosquitoes; no rain
or little rain means no water in breeding sites, so that's a good sign as well."
